lor's degree","year_completed":1780,"field":"Theology preparation","notes":"Graduated Yale 1780. Licensed October 1782 by the Hartford South Association to preach as a candidate."}],"career":[{"title":"Pastor of the Congregational Church","organization":"Congregational Church Southampton (Long Island NY)","dates":"May 25 1785 - April 1 1789","type":"clergy","notes":"Ordained and instituted at Southampton LI on May 25, 1785. Salary £70/year plus 40 cords of wood delivered yearly. Resigned April 1, 1789. Local history records he received 486 members into the church during his Southampton tenure."},{"title":"Pastor of the Harwinton Congregational Church","organization":"Harwinton Congregational Church (Litchfield County CT)","dates":"March 3 1790 - June 1822","type":"clergy","notes":"Installed March 3, 1790. The present (1808) church was erected at a cost of $8,000. Recorded in his memorandum that 'for seven years his salary of $350 was sufficient; but that then the expense of living was nearly doubled.' Worn down by labors of a revival in November 1820, attacked by disease that confined him 77 days. Petitioned for release; in May 1822 the people gave him $1,000 and he was dismissed in June 1822."},{"title":"Member of monthly missions prayer meeting","organization":"Harwinton Church","dates":"established 1815","type":"clergy","notes":"Per Harwinton Church record February 7, 1815: 'conversed on the subject of a monthly prayer meeting for missions.' Williams remarked to a grandson that he and the neighboring ministers were 'about the first in the world to set up and establish the monthly concert of prayer for missions.'"}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","institution_blurb":"Yale College Class of 1780. Followed by son Joshua Lewis Williams (X00266, Yale 1805)."}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["clergy","yale_graduate"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Two pulpits, hundreds of conversions, seventy-seven days down","body":"Joshua served the Southampton Long Island church for four years (1785-1789), receiving 486 members into communion before resigning. He was installed at Harwinton Connecticut in 1790 and stayed thirty-two years. In November 1820, exhausted by a revival, he was confined to the house seventy-seven days; the people of Harwinton gave him a thousand-dollar gift in 1822 and he was released."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"He outlived son and grandson by years","body":"Removing to Bethlehem to live with his youngest son in 1822, the son died in 1831 having graduated Yale and practiced medicine. Joshua then went to the Upper Houses to be with his eldest son Joshua Lewis — who died December 29, 1832, the day before his own son also died at Yale. Father and grandson were buried in one grave January 1, 1833."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Williams Family Genealogy","url":"http://dunhamwilcox.net/bios/williams.htm","notes":"The Williams Family — Rev. Joshua Williams + descendants."},{"short":"WikiTree (online genealogy)","url":"https://www.wikitree.com/"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"joshua-williams-1761"},"X00266":{"id":"X00266","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":["clergy","yale_graduate"],"sources":[{"short":"Cowles Family Genealogy"},{"bib_id":"BIB003"},{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909"},{"short":"Williams Family Genealogy","url":"http://dunhamwilcox.net/bios/williams.htm","notes":"The Williams Family — Rev. Joshua Williams + descendants."}],"death":{"year":1832,"month":12,"day":29,"city":"Cromwell","county":"Middlesex","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0978","date_year":1813,"date_month":11,"date_day":30,"location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1832,"children_ids":["H02322","H02323","H02324","H02325"],"location_city":"Farmington","location_county":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"parents":{"father_id":"X02770","mother_id":"X02771"},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1785,"month":1,"day":21,"city":"Wethersfield","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Rev. Joshua Lewis Williams","first_name":"Joshua","last_name":"Williams","title":"Reverend","middle_name":"Lewis","married_names":[],"nickname":"Priest Williams"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","institution_blurb":"Yale Class of 1805 — second-generation Yale graduate following father Rev. Joshua Williams (Yale 1780)."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"title":"Pastor of the Congregational Church","organization":"Congregational Church of the Upper Houses (later Cromwell CT)","dates":"June 10, 1809 - December 29, 1832","type":"clergy","notes":"Ordained and instituted pastor at the Upper Houses (now Cromwell Middlesex County CT) on June 10, 1809 — his father Rev. Joshua Williams Sr. assisted in his ordination. Spoken of locally as 'priest Williams.' Owned the house built by Rev. Gershom Bulkeley, later known as the 'Joseph Edwards House.' Pastor for 23 years until his death."},{"title":"Founding President of the Friendly Association","organization":"Friendly Association (Upper Houses)","dates":"founded by Williams","type":"civic","notes":"Organized the Friendly Association, was its first president, and active in its support throughout his life."},{"title":"Scribe of the General Association of Connecticut","organization":"General Association of Connecticut","dates":"1825 (at Litchfield)","type":"clergy","notes":"Served as scribe at the 1825 Litchfield meeting of the General Association of Connecticut."}],"education":[{"institution":"Yale College","degree":"Bachelor's degree","year_completed":1805,"field":"Theology","notes":"Graduated Yale 1805 — followed his father's 1780 Yale graduation."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Father and Yale-student son buried in one grave","body":"Joshua Lewis died December 29, 1832 in the Upper Houses at age 47. The next day his eldest son John Mix Williams — a seventeen-year-old Yale student — also died. Father and son were buried in one grave January 1, 1833 per Joshua Lewis's own written instruction, though they were given separate headstones."}],"slug":"joshua-williams-1785"},"HD0978":{"id":"HD0978","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00263","mother_id":"H00437"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Cowles Family Genealogy"},{"bib_id":"BIB003"},{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909"},{"short":"Find a Grave — Memento Mori Cemetery Farmington CT","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/53048/memento-mori-cemetery"}],"birth":{"year":1787,"month":12,"day":1,"city":"Farmington","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1863,"month":10,"day":23,"country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00266","marriage_number":1,"children_ids":["H02322","H02323","H02324","H02325"],"date_year":1813,"date_month":11,"date_day":30,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1832,"location_country":"United States","location_city":"Farmington","location_county":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_